  "dateModified": "2026-03-03",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "The structural condition in which intellectual labor is organized as a production process — thought converted into narrative products (threads, essays, papers, podcasts, newsletters) packaged for recognizability within a genre and evaluated by whether the analysis *feels right*, not by whether it corresponds to material outcomes. Citation operates as containment rather than as analytical claim: the citation signals genre membership, confirms the narrative arc has the right shape, and produces the affective satisfaction the market of circulation demands. Embedded knowledge — knowledge held in place by relations, geographies, and obligations — is extracted, formatted, and circulated as insight, with the formatting itself being what the industry selects for.",
  "name": "Industrial intellectualism",
